  "text": "AddressSanitizer (ASan) is implemented across both LLVM and GCC with distinct components. In LLVM's llvm-project repository: (1) The file compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_interceptors.cpp (github.com/llvm/llvm-project) intercepts various libc functions for memory tracking. The file begins with the comment 'Intercept various libc functions' and provides interceptor implementations for standard library memory operations. (2) The file compiler-rt/lib/asan/asan_rtl.cpp (github.com/llvm/llvm-project) is the main ASan runtime library, containing the ASan initialization code and runtime support functions within the __asan namespace. This file's header identifies it as 'Main file of the ASan run-time library'. (3) The LLVM pass file llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp (github.com/llvm/llvm-project) contains the AddressSanitizer struct and ModuleAddressSanitizer class that implements the IR-level instrumentation pass. The file description states it is 'a memory error detector' that instruments code to find memory bugs. In GCC's gcc-mirror/gcc repository: (4) The file gcc/asan.cc (github.com/gcc-mirror/gcc) implements ASan instrumentation in GCC. It contains the primary function asan_instrument() which orchestrates the instrumentation of the current function, calling transform_statements() to insert runtime checks. The file header identifies it as implementing 'AddressSanitizer, a fast memory error detector'. (5) The header file gcc/asan.h (github.com/gcc-mirror/gcc) provides declarations and constants for ASan functionality, including definitions like ASAN_SHADOW_SHIFT (set to 3), ASAN_RED_ZONE_SIZE, and function declarations for stack protection and poisoning. These files form the core instrumentation infrastructure in both compilers, with LLVM using a pass-based approach at the IR level and GCC using a GIMPLE-level transformation approach."
}

